Participants completed a structured online survey consisting of 28 items divided into two subsections: rumination and academic efficacy. The rumination subsection (10 items) was adapted from the Ruminative Responses Scale and included Q3, Q47, and Q5–Q12. These items measured repetitive and self-focused thought with example questions such as “How often do you think about how sad you feel?” or “I think about the reasons for my feelings,” answered using scales ranging from four-point frequency options (Almost never, Sometimes, Often, Almost always) to five-point Likert scales (Exactly true to Exactly false). Following this block, participants responded to the academic efficacy subsection (18 items), which included Q48, Q49, and Q15.1–Q29. These questions assessed confidence in academic competence and ability to handle coursework, with example items such as “I can always manage to solve difficult academic problems if I try hard enough” and “I feel confident that I can succeed in my coursework,” rated on scales from Strongly disagree to Strongly agree. All items were presented in a fixed order, with the rumination block (Q3, Q47, Q5–Q12) first, followed by the academic efficacy block (Q48–Q49, Q15.1–Q29), ensuring that participants completed the rumination measures before evaluating their academic beliefs. The entire survey took approximately 5–10 minutes to complete, after which participants received a debriefing statement and were thanked for their participation.
